Chase was born with a congenital heart defect called (Tetralogy of Fallot) and he also has a feeding tube placement in his stomach due to Chace not eating orally as a baby. node.text:
As parents we get so busy in our daily lives that we never take a few sec or mins to listen to our (child/children) when they want to talk or show us something.
⠀
All they want to do is make us proud. Something I was doing to My son Chace that I had to stop was always telling him, just give me 5-10mins and I'll be right with you.
⠀⠀⠀
I get so consumed in my work to by time I look up! it's been 1, 2 or even 3hrs later and now my son is sad or mad at me because I couldn't just give him a few sec of my time. Now in his eyes he thinks work, tv, phone etc... is more important to me then he is and what he wanted to tell me isn't as Valuable now.
⠀⠀⠀
As a parent you have to be your (child/children) BIGGEST LISTENER, BIGGEST CHEERLEADER, BIGGEST SUPPORTER, BIGGEST HYPEMAN no matter how silly the story is or how stupid the game is or even how bad the joke might be. Value their words and they will always and forever remember how important they are to you.

Day 11:

Today We're Honoring Vivien Theodore Thomas. He was born August 29, 1910 - November 26, 1985.
Thomas had hoped to attend college and become a doctor, but the Great Depression derailed his plans. 
He worked at Vanderbilt University in the summer of 1929 doing carpentry but was laid off in the fall. In 1930 he secured a job as surgical research technician with Dr. Alfred Blalock at Vanderbilt University. 
Thomas was classified and paid as a janitor, despite the fact he was doing the work of a Postdoctoral researcher in the lab.
In 1943, Thomas was charged with the task of first creating a blue baby-like condition, and then correcting the condition. nearly two years of laboratory work. Vivien Thomas finally solved the blue like baby condition.
Without any education past high school, Thomas rose above poverty and racism to become a cardiac surgery pioneer and a teacher. Thomas' procedure helped save thousands of babies' lives in the 1940s, now his surgical procedure has saved millions of lives.

node.text: I promised myself that I would take a brake from social media for the summer... however I thought I should let you all know that this week I lost my Polly 😭 to pulmonary heart defect! I don’t think I will ever get over this. My heart is broken. I am broken!!! I am not in a place to even talk about it.
